t identical and jittering seems to produce goodresults in this case.TW20@ (Let's activate once again to verify this.)TW10@TW10@€TW10@.±TW10@By default, the scatter plots are automatically scaled.TW10@To produce overlays of plots with the same fixed scales, we can proceedin the following way:TW20@GPLOT WORLD / TYPE=DRAFTS JITTER=10TW10@OUTSCALE=WSCALE.TXTTW10@The last specification saves the ranges and jittering parameters ofthe variables in a text file WSCALE.TXTTW20@TW10@€TW10@TW10@When plotting partial data sets, we employ the scales given in thisfile as follows:TW20@.±±65TW10@INSCALE=WSCALE.TXTTW10@IND=Growth,-1,2.3 (only countries with limited growth)TW10@OUTFILE=A (saving the picture in A.SPX)TW20@TW10@€TW10@.±TW10@Adding countries with Growth over 2.3: (Red dots)TW20@COPY 72,76,78TW10@€TW20@TW10@2.301,10TW10@INFILE=ATW10@ºTW10@ POINT=[RED],0,0TW10@TW10@€TW10@TW10@Individual countries may be studied in the following way:TW10@±78±79TW10@CASES=Country:Finland POINT=[GREEN],0,3TW10@INFILE=ATW10@TW10@€TW10@TW10@USA    TW10@TW10@€TW10@   End of "Draftsman's displays"TW50@0d>DEL =WORLD.SVO€>DEL =*.SPX€Ta1@X0xTa-1@TL!MPLOT0@Tÿ